</math>

<!-- $$d(\langle a_1,a_2 \rangle, \langle b_1,b_2 \rangle) = \sqrt{(a_1 - b_1)^2 + (a_2 - b_2)^2} $$ -->

<p>is a metric on the set ℝ since</p>

<ol type="i">
	<li><p>|<i>a</i> − <i>b</i>| &ge; 0 , for all a and b in ℝ, and |<i>a</i> − <i>b</i>| = 0 if and only if <i>a</i> = <i>b</i>;</p></li>
	<li><p>|<i>a</i> − <i>b</i>| = |<i>b</i> − <i>a</i>|;</p></li>
	<li><p>|<i>a</i> − <i>c</i>| &le; |<i>a</i> − <i>b</i>| + |<i>b</i> − <i>c</i>|. (Deduce this from |<i>x</i> + <i>y</i>| &le; |<i>x</i>| + |<i>y</i>|.)</p></li>
</ol>

<p>We call <i>d</i> the <b>euclidean metric on</b> ℝ.  Yet another metric on ℝ<sup>2</sup> is given by</p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>d</i> (⟨<i>a</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>a</i><sub>2</sub>, <i>b</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>b</i><sub>2</sub>⟩) = |<i>a</i><sub>1</sub> − <i>b</i><sub>1</sub>| + |<i>a</i><sub>2</sub> − <i>b</i><sub>2</sub>|.&emsp;■</p>
</div>

<p><b>Example 3.1.4</b>. Let <i>C</i>[0, 1] denote the set of continuous functions from [0, 1] into ℝ. A metric is defined on this set by</p>

<div class="eq">
<p>∫<sup><sup>1</sup></sup><sub><sub>0</sub></sub> |<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) − <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>)| d<i>x</i></p>
</div>

<p>where <i>f</i> and <i>g</i> are in <i>C</i>[0, 1]. <i>d</i>(<i>f, g</i>) is precisely the area of the region which lies between the graphs of the functions and the lines x = 0 and x = 1, as illustrated below considering the two functions <i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) = 2<i>x</i> − <i>x</i><sup>3</sup> and <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = <i>x</i> − <i>x</i><sup>2</sup>.</p>

<figure>
<img src="../multivariable_calculus/img/ysimple_example.png" alt="y simple not x simple"/>
<figcaption>Region of the plane between <i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) = 2<i>x</i> − <i>x</i><sup>3</sup> and <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>) = <i>x</i> − <i>x</i><sup>2</sup></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Another metric is defined on C [0, 1] as follows:</p>

<div class="eq">
<p>d<sup>∗</sup> (<i>f, g</i>) = sup{|<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) − <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>)| : <i>x</i> ∈ [0, 1]}</p>
</div>

<p>If we try to calculate the metrix for this particular example we find that |<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) − <i>g</i>(<i>x</i>)| = |−<i>x</i><sup>3</sup> + <i>x</i><sup>2</sup> +<i>x</i>|; The maximum value of a differentiable function <i>h</i> on (0,1), is found solving <i>h'</i>(<i>x</i>) = 0 and checking the endpoints 0 and 1. Taking the derivative and equating to zero: −3<i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + 2<i>x</i> + 1 = 0, solving the quadratic equation we find 1 and − 1/3 and considering only the positive solution <i>x</i> = 1; when you put <i>x</i> into |f(x) − g(x)|, it turns out to give 1. &emsp;■</p>

<h2>Open and Closed Sets in ℝ</h2>

<p><b>Proposition 3.17</b>.</p>

<ol>
	<li><p>The empty set ∅ and the set ℝ are open.</p></li>
	<li><p>Every open interval in ℝ is an open set.</p></li>
</ol>

<p><b>Proof</b>.</p>

<ol>
	<li><p>ℝ is clearly open as for every x ∈ ℝ, for any ε > 0, the open ball B<sub>ε</sub>(<i>x</i>) is in ℝ. We see that the empty set ∅ is open by contradiction: if it were not open, then there would exist an x ∈ ∅ for which there is no such ε, but this is a contradiction since there is no x in ∅; therefore, ∅ must be open.</p></li>

	<li><p>Let <i>I</i> be a nonempty open interval, and let x ∈ I. Then I can be a bounded or an unbounded interval. If it is bounded, then it is of the form I = (a, b), for some <i>a, b</i> ∈ ℝ. In this case we can choose ε to be any positive number less than the distance from x to the endpoints, i.e., ε < min{x − a, b − x}. Then the ball centered at <i>x</i> of radius ε must be in I. If I = (a, ∞), let ε = x − a, and if I = (−∞, b), let ε = b − x. In both cases we have that B(x, ε) ⊆ I. Therefore I is open.&emsp;□</p></li>
</ol>

<p>However not all open sets are intervals for example, (1,2) u (4,5) is open. In ℝ, {2} is closed and not open; R is both; [1,3) is neither. </p>

<p><b>Examples. 3.1.7</b>. In ℝ, any open interval (<i>a,b</i>) is an open set: Let <i>x</i> &in; (<i>a,b</i>) and let &epsilon; = min {<i>x</i>−<i>a</i>, <i>b</i> − <i>x</i>}. Then <i>B<sub>&epsilon;</sub></i> (<i>x</i>) = (<i>x</i> − &epsilon;, <i>x</i> + <i>&epsilon;</i>; is an open ball with <i>x</i> as center such that <i>B<sub>&epsilon;</sub></i> (<i>x</i>) &subseteq; (<i>a,b</i>). <br> 
If we add both endpoints to the interval, we have a closed set. Hence the names open and closed interval. <br> The whole line ℝ and any open half-line (<i>a</i>, &infin;) or (−&infin;, <i>a</i>) is an open set. On the other hand, the half-open interval [<i>a,b</i>) is not open, because it contains no neighborhood of the point <i>a</i>.</p>
<p>In ℝ, {0} is not open. &emsp;■</p>

<p><b>Definition 3.1.8</b>. Let (<i>X, d</i>) be a metric space and let <i>A</i> ⊂ <i>X</i>. We say that A is <b>bounded</b> if it is contained in a ball of a finite radius.&emsp;□</p>

